1)Child Process and fork() System Call in Linux/Unix

A child process is a new process created by an existing process, known as the parent process. In Unix/Linux operating systems, a child process is created using the fork() system call.

The fork() system call duplicates the calling process. After a successful fork(), two processes exist:

Parent Process – the original process.
Child Process – the newly created process.

Both processes execute the same program from the point where fork() is called, but they have separate memory spaces and process identifiers (PIDs).
| Return Value | Meaning                                             |
| ------------ | --------------------------------------------------- |
| 0            | Returned to the child process                       |
| > 0          | Returned to the parent process (contains child PID) |
| -1           | Fork failed                                         |

Working of fork()

Parent process calls fork().
Operating system creates a child process.
Child receives a unique PID.
Both parent and child continue execution independently.
