2)Handling Common Signals in Unix/Linux

A signal is a software interrupt sent to a process to notify it of an event that requires immediate attention. Signals provide a mechanism for communication between the operating system and processes, as well as between different processes.

Signal handling allows a program to respond to specific events instead of terminating abruptly. When a signal is received, the process can perform a predefined action such as terminating gracefully, ignoring the signal, or executing a custom signal handler.

Common Signals
1. SIGINT (Interrupt Signal)

Generated when the user presses Ctrl + C from the terminal. It is commonly used to interrupt a running program.

2. SIGTERM (Termination Signal)

Used to request a process to terminate gracefully. This is the default signal sent by the kill command.

3. SIGKILL (Kill Signal)

Forcibly terminates a process immediately. It cannot be caught, blocked, or ignored by the process.

4. SIGSTOP (Stop Signal)

Suspends the execution of a process. Like SIGKILL, it cannot be caught or ignored.

5. SIGCONT (Continue Signal)

Resumes the execution of a process that has been stopped.

6. SIGALRM (Alarm Signal)

Generated when a timer set by the process expires. It is often used for implementing timeouts.

7. SIGCHLD (Child Signal)

Sent to a parent process when one of its child processes terminates or changes state.

8. SIGSEGV (Segmentation Fault Signal)

Occurs when a program attempts to access memory that it is not allowed to access. It usually indicates a programming error.

9. SIGFPE (Floating Point Exception Signal)

Generated when an arithmetic error occurs, such as division by zero.

10. SIGUSR1 and SIGUSR2 (User-Defined Signals)

Reserved for application-specific purposes and can be used for communication between processes.

Signal Handling Process

When a signal is generated, the operating system delivers it to the target process. The process may:

Execute the default action associated with the signal.
Ignore the signal.
Invoke a custom signal handler to perform specific actions.

