Different Types of Kernel Crashes

A kernel crash occurs when the operating system kernel encounters a critical error from which it cannot safely recover. Since the kernel manages memory, processes, devices, and hardware resources, a crash usually results in a system halt, reboot, or panic screen.

1. Kernel Panic

A kernel panic is the most common kernel crash in Linux and Unix systems. It occurs when the kernel detects an unrecoverable error.

Causes
Invalid memory access
Corrupted kernel data structures
Faulty device drivers
Hardware failures
Effect
System stops functioning.
Diagnostic information is displayed.
Usually requires a reboot.

2. Null Pointer Dereference

Occurs when the kernel attempts to access memory through a NULL pointer.

Causes
Programming bugs in kernel code
Driver errors
Effect
Immediate kernel exception
Often leads to kernel panic
3. Page Fault in Kernel Mode

A page fault occurs when the kernel accesses memory that is not present or is invalid.

Causes
Invalid memory references
Corrupted pointers
Driver bugs
Effect
Kernel panic or system halt

4. Stack Overflow

Every kernel thread has a limited stack size. Excessive recursion or large local variables can exhaust the stack.

Causes
Infinite recursion
Deep function call chains
Effect
Memory corruption
System crash

5. Divide-by-Zero Exception

Occurs when kernel code performs division by zero.

Causes
Arithmetic programming errors
Effect
CPU exception generated
Kernel crash if not handled

6. General Protection Fault (GPF)

Generated when the CPU detects illegal operations or invalid memory accesses.

Causes
Accessing restricted memory
Invalid instructions
Corrupted pointers
Effect
Kernel panic

7. Deadlock

A deadlock occurs when two or more kernel threads wait indefinitely for resources held by each other.

Causes
Improper lock handling
Synchronization bugs
Effect
System freeze or hang

8. Driver-Induced Crash

Faulty device drivers are among the most common causes of kernel crashes.

Causes
Invalid memory access
Incorrect hardware interaction
Resource leaks
Effect
System instability
Kernel panic

9. Hardware-Induced Crash

Hardware failures can trigger kernel crashes.

Causes
Faulty RAM
CPU errors
Disk corruption
Overheating
Effect
Random crashes
Data corruption

10. Watchdog Timeout

A watchdog timer monitors system responsiveness.

Causes
Infinite loops in kernel code
Deadlocks
Unresponsive drivers
Effect
Forced system reset
Crash reports generated
