Time Complexity

Time Complexity is a measure of the amount of time an algorithm takes to execute as the size of the input increases. It helps in analyzing the efficiency of an algorithm and comparing different algorithms independent of the computer's hardware or software.

Time complexity is usually expressed using Big O notation, which describes how the running time grows with input size n.

Importance of Time Complexity
Helps compare different algorithms.
Predicts performance for large inputs.
Assists in selecting efficient solutions.
Reduces execution time and resource usage.
Asymptotic Notations
1. Big O Notation – O()

Represents the upper bound or worst-case performance of an algorithm.

Example:

Linear Search → O(n)
Bubble Sort → O(n²)
2. Omega Notation – Ω()

Represents the lower bound or best-case performance.

Example:

Linear Search → Ω(1)

when the element is found at the first position.

3. Theta Notation – Θ()

Represents the exact bound when upper and lower bounds are the same.

Example:

Merge Sort → Θ(n log n)

