Mutex Locking Mechanism
Introduction

In a multithreaded environment, multiple threads may attempt to access and modify shared resources simultaneously. This can lead to inconsistencies in data and unpredictable program behavior. To avoid such problems, synchronization mechanisms are used. One of the most commonly used synchronization techniques is the Mutex (Mutual Exclusion).

A mutex is a locking mechanism that ensures only one thread can access a shared resource or critical section at a time. It helps maintain data integrity and prevents race conditions.

Definition

A Mutex (Mutual Exclusion) is a synchronization object used to control access to a shared resource by multiple threads. When a thread acquires a mutex lock, no other thread can access the protected resource until the mutex is released.

Need for Mutex

When multiple threads access the same resource concurrently, conflicts may occur. For example, if two threads attempt to update the same variable simultaneously, the final result may become incorrect. Such situations are known as race conditions.

Mutexes are used to:

Prevent race conditions.
Protect shared resources.
Ensure data consistency.
Synchronize thread execution.
Working of a Mutex

The operation of a mutex involves two basic actions:

1. Lock Operation

Before entering the critical section, a thread requests the mutex lock. If the mutex is available, the thread acquires it and proceeds. If another thread already holds the lock, the requesting thread is blocked until the mutex becomes available.

2. Unlock Operation

After completing its work within the critical section, the thread releases the mutex. Once unlocked, another waiting thread can acquire the mutex and access the shared resource.

The sequence of operations is:

Thread Requests Lock
        ↓
Mutex Available?
        ↓
      Yes
        ↓
Enter Critical Section
        ↓
Perform Operations
        ↓
Release Lock
        ↓
Other Threads Can Proceed
Critical Section

A critical section is the part of a program where shared resources are accessed or modified. Since multiple threads may attempt to execute this section simultaneously, synchronization is required.

Examples of shared resources include:

Global variables
Shared memory
Files
Buffers
Databases

Mutexes ensure that only one thread can execute the critical section at a time.
